      <description>Hello again,&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I wanted to let folks know there's been some good fixes lately and I wanted to talk about them a bit because people seem to like to know these details. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The last 'collision update' post was here -  http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=development&amp;message.id=2007 - I'll try to answer what I can from there, but first let me go over some recent bug fixes.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;As some folks may have heard, we introduced new networking code on Test a couple weeks ago. This code has made a tremendous difference to the coders because it provides a wealth of great debugging features that have made it easier than ever to solve some really difficult bugs that have been around for a while. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The first bug that was fixed was related to subtle differences in the way that the zone servers and the clients load geometry. Turns out that objects (but not the terrain) on the zone server had their "triangle normals" pointed in the opposite direction for zones created using the new DX9 data format (EQG files). This was causing problems for NPC pathing and any other server code that depending on being able to "find the ground" when standing on top of one of these objects (as opposed to the standard terrain geometry). Many Omens of War zones had a number of places where entire sections of the zone were using this type of geometry, such as the tunnels in the bloodfields, and this would cause all kinds of problems with pathing, summoning pets, and things of that nature. After this problem was finally identified thanks to some debugging features we've recently added, it was easy to fix and seems to have helped a lot. This fix went in with today’s update.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The second bug that appears to be fixed is related to a combination of events that could cause the zone server to think a player was falling under the world even when the player appeared to be above the world in the correct location for all clients. I say 'appears' because it hasn't been fully tested yet by other people, but it is working on my development servers at least. It's related to the way the physics system extrapolates positions over time and how gravity is part of the position extrapolation. There is a check that is made that was intended to prevent extrapolation from going below ground level, but the problem was that the ground level check was sometimes producing invalid values. This could happen when the extrapolation happened after receiving a network packet and the extrapolated movement had not yet been collision checked. Once the server had an invalid ground elevation, it was unable to correct itself and the server data usually had the player falling under the world when this happened. It wasn't seen by the clients directly because the extrapolation is used only by the zone server; each client does their own extrapolation. While it wasn’t seen directly by the clients, players did see the side effects of this bug. For example, MGB/Group spells would sometimes not hit everyone in the group because the server thought some of the players were on the surface and some could be literally thousands of units below (as a result of the server's extrapolation of gravity over time). The problem of spells not landing in a couple of specific situations was a reproducible problem that no longer occurs now that this bug has been fixed. I suspect it will correct a number of other hard to reproduce problems related to getting summoned under the world for various reasons, picking up agro from floors below you, and things of that nature but I'm still trying to find reproducible test cases to be sure. Unfortunately, this fix was only recently made and hasn’t yet been tested carefully enough to put into this update. Look for it to hit Test sometime soon, though.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Now, getting to the previous thread with all the questions about collision &amp; movement types of problems, I’ll answer what I can:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Axxius – “However, there was this question about a bug related to collision: in some zones (Uqua comes to mind), walking close to a wall when shrunk switches your first person view camera to a ducking mode even though you are not ducking and have auto-duck off. You just start seeing things from a lower height as if you were ducking. Is this fixed now?”&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;No, this hasn’t been worked on. I can tell you what the source of this is however. I think most people have seen how small races can see through walls pretty easily just by walking up to them. This is actually the oldest bug I’ve worked on in the database, which was entered - . We added code to the camera system to try to prevent this from happening and for a while it was working but not long after that some seemingly unrelated changes broke both this fix and also allowed small races to see through walls again. It’s on my list of things to fix but I don’t have an ETA.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Pomaikai - " Is anything being done about the Z-Axis collision bug for those on a mount in Vex Thal?  If you are on a mount you will agro mobs on the floors directly above and below you.”&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I haven’t tested this problem recently, but last time we tested it (horses in VT) everything seemed to be working fine with respect to agro distance &amp; other related stuff. Looking back, however, I don’t think we tested it in such a way that would trigger the bug #2 above and I suspect this has been fixed. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Tyck- “I'd like to suggest testing using a shaman using bearform with different level's of shrink.”&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I’ve been doing my testing lately with all kinds of sizes, we have a GM command to allow us to easily set any size/model we want. Since the two bugs described above were fixed on my machine, I haven’t seen any problems so I am hopeful this sort of thing is finally fixed. We’ll test it more when I wrap up what I’m doing and get all this on Test.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;ChatHandle_03 &amp; twoofus, I’ve forwarded your suggestions about /outputfile. No promises but this sort of thing is obviously pretty easy. I’m hoping to enhance this output enough that people won’t feel the need to run memory sniffers to get the character data they want.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Eludril, I’ve forwarded your comments about the guild tool window. Should be easy to fix.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;PimpDaddyFroglok – “How about you finally fix the run speed prediction on the client for mobs that aren't in the view? It's absurd that you get 'Your target is out of range' spell message for monsters that aren't in the view that are hitting you in the back.”&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Yeah that would be no fun to deal with. I thought this had long since been fixed though, perhaps it only went in with the 12/16 update though. Please let me know if this is still happening, because I thought it had been fixed and I don't have a bug for this in my bug database.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Ixiola – The reports of people 20k’ing after getting a COH have been difficult for me to reproduce. In fact, I haven’t yet been able to get it to happen at all and QA has only been able to get it to happen sporadically. We’ll keep trying to get a repro case though.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;MordenX, I think the problem you had with getting stuck in the ceiling is probably directly related to some other bugs that were fixed on 12/16. Is this still happening?&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Mooncage, “in East Cabilis, my Iksar has to duck in order to get into a few buildings, and also to walk across one of the "board bridges" in the middle of the zone (sort of near the Monk guild).  I'm not sure if it's related to his headgear, which has the large skull graphic.“&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I think this was probably fixed with the 12/16 update. Please let me know if it’s still doing this.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;2ul_Rocks, I’ll take a closer look at wall of slaughter. That zone has a lot of models that would affect collisions/pathing as a result of bug#1 (above) and that is probably what you are seeing there, hopefully it will be corrected by the fix. The pathing comments are a bit more troubling though, I’ll see what is going on there.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Sarshish, I expect the bug#1 is the cause of the problem with chimeras in riftseekers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Disembowel, the warping mobs in Vxed are probably pathing failures of some sort. I have spent a lot of time lately adding diagnostic code that will allow me to debug pathing much more easily so I am hoping for progress on pathing issues fairly soon.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Velvaren, if what I suspect is true then the pathing problems people are describing are probably common to all Omens zones as you describe. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Maximin &amp; skaal, I think the mount related and veksar pathing bugs are almost certainly related to bug#2. I haven’t yet been able to verify this however.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;MrHamster, the “you cannot see your target” messages related to line of sight when casting, etc, have been somewhat improved by bugfix#2, but we’re discussing how to increase visibility between players and their targets. Right now it only does one line of sight check, and we’re talking about doing more checks to different parts of the body to more accurately represent visibility. We are only in the discussion stage however.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Conejo, the zone has code in place that should be warping NPCs up to the surface when they go under the world as a result of either collision bug or simply the absense of a floor to keep them falling (aka an art bug). I’ll take a look at these zones to make sure the parameters for making this work with the geometry in those zones is correct.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Please feel free to post here with any more information or questions about outstanding collision/pathing bugs that still exist after today's update.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Cheers,</description>
